**Copyright © 2026 Arvind Ji ([@official-Arvind](https://github.com/official-Arvind))**

Hey! Welcome to Jigar Tools. This project is free, made with love, and meant to stay that way. Read this once — it's short and written like a human being wrote it. 

---

## ✅ What You CAN Do (Go Wild)

- **Use it personally** — back up your own phone, your family's phone, your friend's phone. Go nuts.
- **Contribute** — fork it, improve it, fix bugs, add features. Send a PR. You're part of this now.
- **Learn from it** — study the code, use the techniques, get smarter. That's the whole point.
- **Use it in your own app or project** — embed it, build on top of it, integrate it into your tool. Totally fine, with the two simple rules below.
- **Share it** — tell people about it, link to it, recommend it. The more the merrier.
- **Modify it** — change things to fit your needs, customize it, make it your own. Just remember: if you share it, keep it free and give credit.

---

## ⚠️ Two Simple Rules (That's It)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Rule 1 — Keep It Free**
> 
> If you use this code in your app or project, **your app must be free**. No paid downloads, no subscriptions, no "premium tier" that includes this code. 
> 
> "Free" means:
> - No upfront cost to download, install, or use
> - No paywalls hiding core features that rely on this code
> - Ad-supported and community-funded projects are fine — as long as the code itself stays accessible to everyone
> 
> Open source is made for people, by people. Keep that spirit alive.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Rule 2 — Give Credit**
> 
> If you use this code anywhere, you must:
> 1. Clearly state that this code was created by **Arvind Ji**
> 2. Include a link to the official repository: **https://github.com/official-Arvind/jigar-tools**
> 3. Credit should be visible and easy to find (in your README, about page, or footer — wherever makes sense for your project)

That's it. Two rules. Not complicated.

---

## 🚫 The One Thing That Will Make Arvind Ji Unhappy

> [!CAUTION]
> **Do not sell this.** 
> 
> Do not take this code, slap a price tag on it, and sell it to people who don't know it was free. That's the only thing this license truly forbids. Everything else is fair game if you follow the two simple rules above.
> 
> If someone asks "is this code free?", the honest answer should be "yes" — not "yes, but I wrapped it in something that costs money."

---

## 🎯 Special Cases (So You Don't Have to Guess)

**Commercial Companies & Enterprise Use:**
- Your business can use this internally for free — no charge there.
- But if you're selling a product/service that directly includes this code, that product must stay free and your users must know the source.
- Contact Arvind Ji if you want to discuss specific use cases — we can probably work something out.

**Freemium Models & Optional Paid Features:**
- You can have a "free" core and a "paid" premium tier, as long as the features using this code are in the free tier.
- The paid parts can't depend on or include this code.

**Educational & Non-Profit:**
- Universities, coding bootcamps, open-source projects, nonprofits — use it freely. Just give credit.

**Forks & Derivative Works:**
- When you fork this, your fork must follow the same rules.
- No sneaking around the license by forking and claiming it as your own.

---



## 📋 Summary (Plain English)

| Action | Allowed? |
|---|---|
| Use for personal backup | ✅ Yes |
| Use in a free app or project | ✅ Yes *(with credit + link)* |
| Modify for your own use | ✅ Yes |
| Contribute to the project | ✅ Yes, please! |
| Share and recommend | ✅ Yes |
| Internal company use | ✅ Yes *(no need to credit internally)* |
| Ad-supported free app | ✅ Yes *(if free to users + credit given)* |
| Use in a **paid** app or product | 🚫 No |
| Sell this code | 🚫 No |
| Distribute without credit | 🚫 No |
| Hide that this is free/open-source | 🚫 No |

